<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Document: a document in the handwriting of the author ]">AD</abbr>, <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 1, 1750-72, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger A</span>, 340, 344.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GW assumed the management of Poseys ferry at Mount Vernon when he began renting it in 1770 prior to buying it in 1772. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0136&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0136-fn-0002#GEWN-02-08-02-0136-fn-0002" class="document">John West, Jr., to GW, 26 April 1769, n.2</a>. At some time this month, GW petitioned the Charles County (Md.) court to open and maintain the road that leads from Portobacco Road to Mr [Thomas Hanson] Marshalls land opposite to poseys Ferry which Said Road is Very much frequented by Travellers. The court ordered Benjamin Ward and Peter Dent to View the within Road and make Report thereof to the next Court (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Maryland Hall of Records Commission, Annapolis ]">MdAA</span>: Charles County Court Records, Liber T, no. 3 [177072], 376).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Francis Whiting (d. 1775) paid GW for the weaving of 7 yds of a 1100 Jeans, delivered 18 June 1770 (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 1, 1750-72, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger A</span>, 126). In 1773 Whiting rented a parcel of GWs Bullskin land in Frederick County.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0003">3</a>
 
   <p>On 2 Aug. GW was At home all day a writing Letters &amp; Advertisements of Harry who run away the 29th. Ulto (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Donald Jackson and Dorothy Twohig, eds. &lt;i&gt;The Diaries of George Washington&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Charlottesville, Va., 197679. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Diaries</span></span>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-01-03-02-0001-0019" class="document">3:45</a>). Harry was a slave on the new farm by the ferry at Mount Vernon. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0325" class="document">Memorandum: List of Tithables, 14 June 1771</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0042" class="document">10 June 1772</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>This was initial payment for James Clevelands share of wheat made under his management at River farm (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Manuscript Ledger Book 1, 1750-72, in George Washington Papers, Library of Congress. ]">Ledger A</span>, 312).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>GW was in Alexandria on 19, 20, and 21 Aug. for the meeting of the Fairfax County court. He spent the night of 20 Aug. at his new house on the corner of Pitt and Cameron streets.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0006-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0006">6</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0288&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0288-fn-0002#GEWN-02-08-02-0288-fn-0002" class="document">January 1771 Cash Accounts, n.2</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0007-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0340-fn-0007">7</a>

   <p>James Connell was a cabinetmaker. He worked on GWs new house in Alexandria (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0217&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0217-fn-0007#GEWN-02-08-02-0217-fn-0007" class="document">Cash Accounts, April 1770, n.7</a>).</p>

</div>
</div>
